{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487562"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:14:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:14:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"391"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/391"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.19,0.02,0.04,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"391"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60553"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/391"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"391"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45978"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1158"},{"type":"tags","id":"1343"},{"type":"tags","id":"1777"},{"type":"tags","id":"2936"},{"type":"tags","id":"3584"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44457"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45049"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60553"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 49-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a two month history of intermittent greenish discharge from her left nipple. Over the last five months her periods have become irregular and she is experiencing hot flushes, decreased libido and insomnia. She does not take any medications, drinks about four glasses of wine a week and has a 10 pack-year smoking history. On examination of the breasts no abnormalities are visible. There is no tenderness or masses appreciable on palpation. With gentle pressure around the areola, a small quantity of green discharge is expressed from several ducts on the left nipple (Image). There is no axillary lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mammary duct ectasia","Intraductal papilloma","Fibrocystic changes","Hyperprolactinaemia","Ductal carcinoma in situ"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMammary duct ectasia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there is dilatation of the major ducts behind the nipple. The duct walls thicken with build-up of fluid and debris leading to a green-brown discharge. Inflammation can arise in these blocked ducts (periductal mastitis), which can lead to nipple inversion. Duct ectasia is the most common cause of greenish nipple discharge. Findings that support this diagnosis include the correct age (45-55 years during the perimenopausal period) and green coloured discharge from several ducts. A firm, stable, subareolar mass can be felt in some cases of mammary duct ectasia, but any discrete mass should be investigated on its own merits to exclude an associated malignancy. Smoking is associated with mammary duct ectasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntraductal papilloma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign proliferation from the epithelium of the lactiferous ducts. It can be divided into solitary or multiple benign lesions. It is the most common cause of bloody or serous nipple discharge and is the most common papillary breast lesion. There may be a palpable breast tumour close to or behind the nipple or areola. Although this condition is a common cause of nipple discharge, it does not commonly cause green discharge and is usually bloody or serous. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrocystic changes \u003C/strong\u003Eare the most common benign changes of the breast. These benign changes are characterised by the formation of fibrotic and/or cystic tissue in the breast. It most commonly occurs in premenopausal women and usually presents as bilateral multifocal breast pain prior to menses. Nipple discharge is uncommon in this condition, but if present the discharge is usually clear or milky in colour.  This patient had unilateral discharge which decreases the likelihood of fibrocystic change as the cause and the discharge was green rather than clear or milky. Fibrocystic changes do not cause nipple inversion and commonly have a relation to menses (cyclical).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperprolactinaemia\u003C/strong\u003E causes a physiological nipple discharge which is characterised by bilateral milky nipple discharge and other symptoms of high prolactin such as decreased libido, amenorrhea and vaginal atrophy. Galactorrhoea more commonly occurs in premenopausal women, which this patient is not. Some of the symptoms of high prolactin overlap with perimenopausal symptoms however the clinical picture such as the woman\u0027s age, the absence of bilateral milky discharge from several ducts points towards these symptoms being related to menopause rather than hyperprolactinaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuctal carcinoma in situ \u003C/strong\u003Eaccounts for 5-15% of cases of pathological nipple discharge. DCIS usually produces a spontaneous blood-stained discharge from a single duct on one breast. DCIS does not usually present with a breast mass or axillary lymphadenopathy. Although these features are absent in this particular case, and DCIS it is not the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s discharge, further imaging should be performed to exclude an underlying malignancy, particularly in this age group.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mammary duct ectasia is the most common cause of greenish nipple discharge","Intraductal papilloma is the most common cause of bloody or serous nipple discharge","Pathological nipple discharge is unilateral, non milky discharge"],"references":["Parthasarathy V, Rathnam U. Nipple discharge: an early warning sign of breast cancer. Int J Prev Med. 2012 Nov;3(11):810-4.. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3506094/","Hamwi MW, Winters R. Mammary Duct Ectasia. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557665/","Nunez D, Gonzalez F, Ibarguengoitia et al. Papillary lesions of the breast: a review. Breast Cancer Management. 2020;9(4). Available at: https://www.futuremedicine.com/doi/10.2217/bmt-2020-0028#_i31"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45978"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"391"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20571"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20571"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/D9LUvil8gGj9u2A2xyRjdWDUn4ssk1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/D9LUvil8gGj9u2A2xyRjdWDUn4ssk1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45978"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-13T00:35:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-13T00:35:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"391"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60553"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1